Sep 14 2009 	Couldn't ask for better place	We stayed 6 nights in August for £420.00. We pre-requested a lower floor room and upon 5pm check-in we were given a ground floor room. As my husband took our 8 very large bags to the room, the clerk Edward volunteered the use of the office to store bags as we had too much to fit in the room (his humble opinion!) . My husband neglected to tell me this, so I proceeded to unpack what we needed for this leg of our 7 week European adventure. I left the camping gear and assorted camping-related items and excess clothing in luggage which I stored under the bed and on top of the armoire. Everything fit except for 1 large suitcase. (all our bags were at the maximum size for airline regulations) The rooms are small, but if all you need is a place to sleep, it is perfect. Our room was not much larger than our tent (8x8), with just enough room to walk around the double-sized bed - no passing! The bed was quite comfortable and, as all of the beds we slept on in Europe, was on a sheet of plywood. The bathroom was tiny with shower, sink and toilet - occupancy: 1. We were leery that the window could not be locked and several ladders were just outside in the courtyard and alley. Edward assured us that it has been like that for 8 years and nothing has ever happened! Of course there is no air conditioning, so the window was opened until we left for sightseeing. We closed the window when we left only to find it propped open with a piece of wood by the cleaning staff. So the window stayed open for the rest of our stay with no incidents.The very good 'traditional English breakfast' is served 7-9am (7:45-9:30 Sundays) in a basement room with tables seating 4 or 3. And don't be 2 minutes late or you don't get served! The first day we got the standard - 1 each bacon, sausage, egg; beans, toast, orange juice, and coffee or hot tea. By now we have had our fill of beans for breakfast and customized our breakfast by substituting an extra egg instead of the beans. Cold cereal and hot chocolate also available. The hostess was not a 'people person' and rarely smiled. BUT she was fast and efficient. So we just accepted it and stacked our dishes when we were finished to help her out. Oh, and left a small tip daily which brought a smile the next day.The night clerk, Edward, was extremely helpful. He arranged for a cab to the airport, the driver told us this was an unexpected gesture from his experience. The cab driver also went beyond the basic and dropped us off at the ground floor entrance, meaning he had to enter the parking garage, get a ticket, drive in circles down a couple of levels, unload us and our bags, then exit the garage (10 minutes free before a parking charge). The day clerk, a young lady, barely looked up for her web browsing to acknowledge people passing the desk. Another perk was free internet access - only in the lobby with the cable provided. So if someone else was using it, you waited your turn. But most were considerate and didn't monopolize it.All in all, this was an extremely pleasant experience and we will definitely stay here on our next trip to London. It is 1 1/2 blocks to King's Cross underground. A great pub is a few blocks away. We ate at Skinner's Arms 4 out of 6 nights and everything we ate was WONDERFUL! It was also the cheapest priced out of the 7 weeks we were in Europe.	
