Jul 3 2008 	You get what you pay for	Hottest day of the year so far, as I strolled into Argyle Square, stopped, looked around at all the other 'hotels' nestling alongside one another in their respective terraced facades, and girded my loins. The chap on reception seemed nice enough, but there the fun ended. I'd booked a double room for myself as it was quite a good price, but, as with most London hotels, it was a bit pokey. The en suite shower was tiny, only 5 channels on the 14&quot; telly, no telephone, no air con, no fridge or mini bar, and the creaking floor boards from the room above, especially in the small hours, truly reflected the price. And it was so hot, even with the tiny fan at full tilt. The next morning, feeling very fluffy from my previous nifghts' combination of too much fire water at the Scala, and not much kip, I ventured downstairs to the cramped breakfast room and asked for scrambled eggs and bacon and a cup of tea. The scrambled eggs were microwaved and resembled an omlette, and one rasher of bacon? I asked for some mushrooms. ' We don't do the mushrooms'. Fried tomatoes? 'We don't do the tomatoes'.After breakfast I settled up and left. But for 65 quid I should really stop moaning. Even the missus says I'm a fussy git when we go anywhere. Maybe that's why she didn't come.	
